No doubt, yes. But why didn't they call it "TestFlight 2" then? A
demonstration flight is a different thing than a test flight or a
development flight. When you test, you expect problems and errors, you
*do* the test to learn about problems, even to the extent to provoke
problems. When you do a demo, you except the thing to work and you do the
demo to demonstrate that it works, even to the extent that you try to
avoid doing things you're not sure about. Testing is engineering,
demoing is marketing.

Silly wording discussion, that. Still, when I demonstrate a software to
a client and it fails to accomplish the mission and then weasel out with
"Err, this actually was a test run and not a demo" I take flak and
rightly so. When you're overconfident and call a test run a "demo"
you'll look silly when what you're finally demonstrating is how to botch
up stage separation and a control system that can't cope with propellant
sloshing induced by the botched separation. Fine outcome for a test
flight (you've found a problem and gathered data to understand and fix
it), bad outcome for a demo (you did demonstrate the wrong thing and
have people talk about success or not).

This does *not* mean that SpaceX hasn't done a fine job so far, mind
you. They just should have used a dictionary before naming the flight.

Jochem

