And the Delta IV-H was heavily based on the Delta IV-M, which had three
successful launches.  When you can point to that sort of design heritage, at
a company with a long history of successful launch vehicles, you expect
success, so you stick a payload on top.  I think the high expectations for
the first launch were justified.

For me, the first Ariane 5 had slightly lower expectations than the Delta
IV-H because there wasn't the same level of design heritage, so it wasn't as
surprising when it failed on the first try.

Falcon I has a lot less (almost nothing) in common with prior, successful
launch vehicles than either Delta IV-H or Ariane 5.  Considering Space-X's
lack of experience and lack of hardware heritage, I always expected they'd
have a steeper learning curve than Boeing.  The first launch was a serious
disappointment because it didn't get far, but the second is very
encouraging, despite the problems and despite the fact that it didn't make
orbit.

I don't think this is a double standard.  I think it's acknowledging the
experience base of the two companies and the design heritage (or lack
thereof) in the vehicles themselves.  I think the people who are crying
double standard aren't looking at the details.  The devil is always in the
details.

