Life in general has this lack of standardization.  Take sports, for
example.  A team of expensive veterans might be considered a failure
if they don't reach the championship game (think New York Yankees).
On the other hand, an expansion team might be considered a huge
success if they reach the second rounds of the playoff.

Or a student from a poor family is considered a success for getting
into a college that a more priviledged family might consider a
failure.

Or stocks - a startup might be a success for losing less money than
expected, where an older and established company can be a failure for
making huge amounts of money, but not as much as anticipated.

This is entirely expected and rational.  A inclusive definition of
success includes at least 3 factors: (1) the performance on the task
at hand,  (2) the amount of resources expended, and (3) the expected
future performance given what is known so far.  This is not some weird
waffing metric designed to disguise failure - this is the one that
people use when voting with their money (making investments) instead
of the strict definition (1) proposed by many here.  This is in spite
of (3) being a very vague criterium.

So I think declaring the Delta-IV heavy a failure while calling SpaceX-
II is success is perfectly rational and not a double standard at all.
It's just using an agueably better definition of success.

(On the other hand, I personally think the Delta-IV heavy was a
roaring success.  Its main objective was to work well enough to
convince the DOD to shut down the Titan line and move all future heavy
launches to the Delta-IV heavy.  At this it succeeded 100%.)

Lou Scheffer
